<div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark"><p>Here’s a concise list of the <strong>general-purpose registers</strong> found in typical CPU architectures, along with their <strong>uses</strong> and key details:</p><hr><h3><strong>1. Accumulator (AC)</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Purpose</strong>: Stores intermediate results of arithmetic and logic operations.</li><li><strong>Usage</strong>: Often used implicitly by arithmetic instructions (e.g., <code>ADD</code>, <code>MUL</code>).</li><li><strong>Example</strong>:<ul><li><code>ADD A</code> → Adds the value in memory location <code>A</code> to the accumulator.</li></ul></li></ul><hr><h3><strong>2. Program Counter (PC)</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Purpose</strong>: Holds the address of the <strong>next instruction</strong> to be executed.</li><li><strong>Usage</strong>: Automatically incremented after each instruction fetch, or updated during a jump/branch.</li><li><strong>Key Role</strong>: Controls program flow.</li></ul><hr><h3>ong>3. Instruction Register (IR)</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Purpose</strong>: Stores the <strong>current instruction</strong> being executed.</li><li><strong>Usage</strong>: Decoded to identify the operation and operands.</li></ul><hr><h3><strong>4. Memory Address Register (MAR)</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Purpose</strong>: Holds the <strong>address</strong> of a memory location to be accessed (read or write).</li><li><strong>Usage</strong>: Sends addresses to memory during instruction fetch or data access.</li></ul><hr><h3><strong>5. Memory Data Register (MDR)</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Purpose</strong>: Holds the <strong>data</strong> being transferred to/from memory.</li><li><strong>Usage</strong>: Acts as a buffer between the CPU and memory.</li></ul><hr><h3><strong>6. Stack Pointer (SP)</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Purpose</strong>: Points to the <strong>top of the stack</strong> in memory.</li><li><strong>Usage</strong>: Used in function calls, returns, and temporary storage of variables.</li></ul><hr><h3><strong>7. Base Register (BR)</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Purpose</strong>: Holds the <strong>starting address</strong> of a memory segment (used in segmented memory models).</li><li><strong>Usage</strong>: Provides a base for calculating effective addresses.</li></ul><hr><h3><strong>8. Index Register (IX / X)</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Purpose</strong>: Holds an <strong>offset</strong> or index value for array access or address calculation.</li><li><strong>Usage</strong>: Used in indexed addressing mode to access elements of arrays or tables.</li></ul><hr><h3><strong>9. General-Purpose Registers (GPRs)</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Purpose</strong>: Multi-use registers for arithmetic, logic, and data storage.</li><li><strong>Examples</strong>: AX, BX, CX, DX in x86 (specific purposes in some architectures).</li><li><strong>Usage</strong>:<ul><li><code>AX</code>: Often acts as the primary accumulator.</li><li><code>BX</code>: Used for base addressing.</li><li><code>CX</code>: Commonly used as a loop counter.</li><li><code>DX</code>: Used for I/O operations and extended precision in division/multiplication.</li></ul></li></ul><hr><h3><strong>10. Flag Register (FR) / Status Register</strong></h3><ul><li><strong>Purpose</strong>: Stores <strong>status flags</strong> (e.g., Zero, Carry, Overflow).</li><li><strong>Usage</strong>: Indicates the outcome of operations for conditional jumps or branches.</li></ul><hr><h3><strong>Summary Table</strong></h3><table><thead><tr><th><strong>Register</strong></th><th><strong>Purpose</strong></th><th><strong>Key Use</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Accumulator (AC)</strong></td><td>Intermediate results</td><td>Arithmetic/logic operations</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Program Counter (PC)</strong></td><td>Address of next instruction</td><td>Controls program flow</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Instruction Register (IR)</strong></td><td>Current instruction</td><td>Decoded for execution</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Memory Address Register (MAR)</strong></td><td>Address for memory access</td><td>Read/write from memory</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Memory Data Register (MDR)</strong></td><td>Data for memory transfer</td><td>Buffer between CPU and memory</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Stack Pointer (SP)</strong></td><td>Top of the stack</td><td>Function calls/returns</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Base Register (BR)</strong></td><td>Starting address of a segment</td><td>Segmented memory models</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Index Register (IX)</strong></td><td>Offset for address calculation</td><td>Indexed addressing</td></tr><tr><td><strong>General-Purpose Registers (GPRs)</strong></td><td>Multi-purpose storage</td><td>Arithmetic, logic, and addressing</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Flag Register (FR)</strong></td><td>Status flags</td><td>Conditional branching</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Let me know if you'd like a more detailed explanation of any of these!</p></div>